{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"8e2e68a1-9c02-4c11-a266-5e3b844dc3aa","content":"`SafeAreaEdges` isn't a built-in .NET MAUI property — that's likely why it has no effect. You need **platform-specific** configuration:\n\n### iOS — disable safe area insets\n\n```xml\n<ContentPage xmlns:ios=\"clr-namespace:Microsoft.Maui.Controls.PlatformConfiguration.iOSSpecific;assembly=Microsoft.Maui.Controls\"\n             ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"False\">\n    <Image Source=\"photo.jpg\" Aspect=\"AspectFill\" />\n</ContentPage>\n```\n\n### Android — enable edge-to-edge\n\nIn your `MainActivity.cs`:\n\n```csharp\nprotected override void OnCreate(Bundle? savedInstanceState)\n{\n    base.OnCreate(savedInstanceState);\n\n    if (Window is not null)\n    {\n        AndroidX.Core.View.WindowCompat.SetDecorFitsSystemWindows(Window, false);\n        Window.SetStatusBarColor(Android.Graphics.Color.Transparent);\n        Window.SetNavigationBarColor(Android.Graphics.Color.Transparent);\n    }\n}\n```\n\n### Key points\n- **iOS**: `ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"False\"` lets content extend behind the notch/home indicator.\n- **Android**: `SetDecorFitsSystemWindows(Window, false)` + transparent bars lets content draw behind system UI.\n- Use `Aspect=\"AspectFill\"` on the `Image` so it fills without distortion.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"6edc1a99-15d2-4285-8536-0dac8c865e68","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about making content go edge-to-edge in a .NET MAUI app, specifically behind the status bar and navigation bar. They've tried `SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"` on the ContentPage but the image still has padding.\n\nThis is a common .NET MAUI question. Let me think about what they need:\n\n1. In .NET MAUI, to go truly edge-to-edge, you need to handle platform-specific configurations.\n2. `SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"` is not a standard MAUI property - they might be confusing it with something else, or it might be a newer API.\n\n\n3. On Android, edge-to-edge mode is the default for apps targeting SDK 35+, but for earlier versions you need to explicitly disable the system window decorations. On iOS, the safe area insets are applied by default and you need to tell the page to ignore them. The user might be referencing a property that doesn't actually exist in standard MAUI. The real solutions are using `ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"False\"` on iOS and handling edge-to-edge on Android through transparency settings and `WindowCompat.SetDecorFitsSystemWindows(window, false)`, though newer .NET versions may have additional APIs for this. I need to correct myself — `SafeAreaEdges` isn't actually a MAUI property, so let me give them the accurate approach instead.","outputTokens":1321,"requestId":"77DA:20A2EF:1894AA:1D649F:69EAC0F3"},"id":"53fb34af-9f2d-4eb0-b4ba-c3489eaf6288","timestamp":"2026-04-24T01:02:02.817Z","parentId":"dce33af6-0e92-4a87-9717-70373d1589e8"}
